 <p>Opir - They sturdy Dwarf</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=valquisssilverpalm>Valquiss Silverpalm</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 627<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(12/6/02 11:23:42 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1941.topic&index=25>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_tongue.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Maxwell</span><hr size=1> With the various explanations that follow, I can agree with the spirit of the post, even though I think one of my comments was partially responsible for this statement.<br>
<br>
Again, as I later replied in this thread, the problem can occur on both sides.  And the funny thing here is Valquiss himself is fairly tolerant, but I work with a lot of people who aren't so I tend to take their view of things.  I don't want to involve anyone else by name here....oh wait, I'll use Bane as an example.  Bane is a good example.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Drizzet:  &quot;No!  I'm a good dark elf.  I'm reformed, you should give me a chance.&quot;<br>
<br>
Bane:  &quot;No Tier'dal is good, because you are spawn of an evil god.  Now crawl back under your rock and stay there.&quot;<br>
<br>
Now, that's role-playing, granted, and that much I will give anyone.  If they are role-playing I'll roleplay back.  But I may well be role-playing being A) intolerant and B) unwilling to co-operate with them or help them.  And that's got to be an acceptable option.<br>
<br>
I've had far too many enounters lately with &quot;non-traditional&quot; character concepts who seem to think I owe them a chance to be my friend. And I don't.  I'll give them their chance to be dismissed in character and with appropriate flourishes, and if they deal with it well and amusingly they'll go on my list of players I appreciate, but that won't change the reaction of my character to their character.<br>
<br>
So yes, I agree with the spirit of this post, I just think the problem is two-sided.  As often as not, it is the good Tier'dal, or whatever, unwilling to accept that the dwarven paladin, or whatever, just isn't going to give him a chance under any conditions to be friends.  He won't accept that the player of that dwarf has a character concept and he just isn't budging.  Well, I don't expect the Tier'dal in question to be evil like all the other Tier'dal just to make my role-playing work, but dammit, the player of that Tier'dal has no right to expect anyone else's character concept to change either, to accomodate them.<br>
<br>
And let's face it, when you insist on doing something so non-traditional you know in advance you are going to be at odds with the rest of the world.  I know it must get frustrating, and I'm sorry, but I'm still not going to change what I'm playing to accomodate anyone else.  Or demand they do the same.<br>
<br>
